# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rollback-strategies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment manages a set of Pods to run an application workload, usually one that doesn't maintain state.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A *Deployment* provides declarative updates for Pods and ReplicaSets.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You describe a *desired state* in a Deployment, and the Deployment Controller changes the actual state to the desired state at a controlled rate.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can define Deployments to create new ReplicaSets, or to remove existing Deployments and adopt all their resources with new Deployments.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Do not manage ReplicaSets owned by a Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Consider opening an issue in the main Kubernetes repository if your use case is not covered below.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The following is an example of a Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Before you begin, make sure your Kubernetes cluster is up and running.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Waiting for rollout to finish: 2 out of 3 new replicas have been updated...
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Run the `kubectl get deployments` again a few seconds later.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to this:Notice that the Deployment has created all three replicas, and all replicas are up-to-date (they contain the latest Pod template) and available.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] To see the ReplicaSet (`rs`) created by the Deployment, run `kubectl get rs`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to this:ReplicaSet output shows the following fields:Notice that the name of the ReplicaSet is always formatted as `[DEPLOYMENT-NAME]-[HASH]`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This name will become the basis for the Pods which are created.The `HASH` string is the same as the `pod-template-hash` label on the ReplicaSet.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] To see the labels automatically generated for each Pod, run `kubectl get pods --show-labels`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to:The created ReplicaSet ensures that there are three `nginx` Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You must specify an appropriate selector and Pod template labels in a Deployment (in this case, `app: nginx`).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Do not overlap labels or selectors with other controllers (including other Deployments and StatefulSets).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Kubernetes doesn't stop you from overlapping, and if multiple controllers have overlapping selectors those controllers might conflict and behave unexpectedly.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The `pod-template-hash` label is added by the Deployment controller to every ReplicaSet that a Deployment creates or adopts.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This label ensures that child ReplicaSets of a Deployment do not overlap.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] It is generated by hashing the `PodTemplate` of the ReplicaSet and using the resulting hash as the label value that is added to the ReplicaSet selector, Pod template labels, and in any existing Pods that the ReplicaSet might have.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] ) is changed, for example if the labels or container images of the template are updated.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Other updates, such as scaling the Deployment, do not trigger a rollout.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Each time a new Deployment is observed by the Deployment controller, a ReplicaSet is created to bring up the desired Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If the Deployment is updated, the existing ReplicaSet that controls Pods whose labels match `.spec.selector` but whose template does not match `.spec.template` is scaled down.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Eventually, the new ReplicaSet is scaled to `.spec.replicas` and all old ReplicaSets is scaled to 0.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you update a Deployment while an existing rollout is in progress, the Deployment creates a new ReplicaSet as per the update and start scaling that up, and rolls over the ReplicaSet that it was scaling up previously -- it will add it to its list of old ReplicaSets and start scaling it down.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, suppose you create a Deployment to create 5 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2`, but then update the Deployment to create 5 replicas of `nginx:1.16.1`, when only 3 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2` had been created.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] In that case, the Deployment immediately starts killing the 3 `nginx:1.14.2` Pods that it had created, and starts creating `nginx:1.16.1` Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] It does not wait for the 5 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2` to be created before changing course.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] It is generally discouraged to make label selector updates and it is suggested to plan your selectors up front.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment's label selector is **immutable** after creation; it cannot be updated via `kubectl patch`, `kubectl edit`, `kubectl apply`, or tools like `helm upgrade`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you must change the selector, you have to delete the Deployment and recreate it.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] By default, deleting the Deployment also deletes its running Pods, causing downtime; use `--cascade=orphan` if you need those Pods to keep running while you recreate the Deployment (see the implications below).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Sometimes, you may want to rollback a Deployment; for example, when the Deployment is not stable, such as crash looping.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] By default, all of the Deployment's rollout history is kept in the system so that you can rollback anytime you want (you can change that by modifying revision history limit).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment's revision is created when a Deployment's rollout is triggered.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] ) is changed, for example if you update the labels or container images of the template.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Other updates, such as scaling the Deployment, do not create a Deployment revision, so that you can facilitate simultaneous manual- or auto-scaling.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This means that when you roll back to an earlier revision, only the Deployment's Pod template part is rolled back.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Waiting for rollout to finish: 1 out of 3 new replicas have been updated...
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Follow the steps given below to rollback the Deployment from the current version to the previous version, which is version 2.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Assuming horizontal Pod autoscaling is enabled in your cluster, you can set up an autoscaler for your Deployment and choose the minimum and maximum number of Pods you want to run based on the CPU utilization of your existing Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] RollingUpdate Deployments support running multiple versions of an application at the same time.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] When you or an autoscaler scales a RollingUpdate Deployment that is in the middle of a rollout (either in progress or paused), the Deployment controller balances the additional replicas in the existing active ReplicaSets (ReplicaSets with Pods) in order to mitigate risk.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, you are running a Deployment with 10 replicas, maxSurge=3, and maxUnavailable=2.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] In our example above, 3 replicas are added to the old ReplicaSet and 2 replicas are added to the new ReplicaSet.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The rollout process should eventually move all replicas to the new ReplicaSet, assuming the new replicas become healthy.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The rollout status confirms how the replicas were added to each ReplicaSet.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] When you update a Deployment, or plan to, you can pause rollouts for that Deployment before you trigger one or more updates.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] When you're ready to apply those changes, you resume rollouts for the Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This approach allows you to apply multiple fixes in between pausing and resuming without triggering unnecessary rollouts.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You cannot rollback a paused Deployment until you resume it.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment enters various states during its lifecycle.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] It can be progressing while rolling out a new ReplicaSet, it can be complete, or it can fail to progress.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can monitor the progress for a Deployment by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This `Progressing` condition will retain a status value of `"True"` until a new rollout is initiated.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The condition holds even when availability of replicas changes (which does instead affect the `Available` condition).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can check if a Deployment has completed by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If the rollout completed successfully, `kubectl rollout status` returns a zero exit code.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Your Deployment may get stuck trying to deploy its newest ReplicaSet without ever completing.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] One way you can detect this condition is to specify a deadline parameter in your Deployment spec: (`.spec.progressDeadlineSeconds`).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] `.spec.progressDeadlineSeconds` denotes the number of seconds the Deployment controller waits before indicating (in the Deployment status) that the Deployment progress has stalled.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This condition can also fail early and is then set to status value of `"False"` due to reasons as `ReplicaSetCreateError`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Also, the deadline is not taken into account anymore once the Deployment rollout completes.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] See the Kubernetes API conventions for more information on status conditions.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Higher level orchestrators can take advantage of it and act accordingly, for example, rollback the Deployment to its previous version.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you pause a Deployment rollout, Kubernetes does not check progress against your specified deadline.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can safely pause a Deployment rollout in the middle of a rollout and resume without triggering the condition for exceeding the deadline.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You may experience transient errors with your Deployments, either due to a low timeout that you have set or due to any other kind of error that can be treated as transient.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, let's suppose you have insufficient quota.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can address an issue of insufficient quota by scaling down your Deployment, by scaling down other controllers you may be running, or by increasing quota in your namespace.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you satisfy the quota conditions and the Deployment controller then completes the Deployment rollout, you'll see the Deployment's status update with a successful condition (`status: "True"` and `reason: NewReplicaSetAvailable`).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] `type: Available` with `status: "True"` means that your Deployment has minimum availability.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Minimum availability is dictated by the parameters specified in the deployment strategy.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can check if a Deployment has failed to progress by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] `kubectl rollout status` returns a non-zero exit code if the Deployment has exceeded the progression deadline.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] All actions that apply to a complete Deployment also apply to a failed Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can scale it up/down, roll back to a previous revision, or even pause it if you need to apply multiple tweaks in the Deployment Pod template.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can set `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` field in a Deployment to specify how many old ReplicaSets for this Deployment you want to retain.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The rest will be garbage-collected in the background.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Explicitly setting this field to 0, will result in cleaning up all the history of your Deployment thus that Deployment will not be able to roll back.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The cleanup only starts **after** a Deployment reaches a complete state.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you set `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` to 0, any rollout nonetheless triggers creation of a new ReplicaSet before Kubernetes removes the old one.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Even with a non-zero revision history limit, you can have more ReplicaSets than the limit you configure.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, if pods are crash looping, and there are multiple rolling updates events triggered over time, you might end up with more ReplicaSets than the `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` because the Deployment never reaches a complete state.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you want to roll out releases to a subset of users or servers using the Deployment, you can create multiple Deployments, one for each release, following the canary pattern described in managing resources.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] As with all other Kubernetes configs, a Deployment needs `.apiVersion`, `.kind`, and `.metadata` fields.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For general information about working with config files, see deploying applications, configuring containers, and using kubectl to manage resources documents.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] When the control plane creates new Pods for a Deployment, the `.metadata.name` of the Deployment is part of the basis for naming those Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The name of a Deployment must be a valid DNS subdomain value, but this can produce unexpected results for the Pod hostnames.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For best compatibility, the name should follow the more restrictive rules for a DNS label.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment also needs a `.spec` section.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The `.spec.template` and `.spec.selector` are the only required fields of the `.spec`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] It has exactly the same schema as a Pod, except it is nested and does not have an `apiVersion` or `kind`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] In addition to required fields for a Pod, a Pod template in a Deployment must specify appropriate labels and an appropriate restart policy.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For labels, make sure not to overlap with other controllers.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Only a `.spec.template.spec.restartPolicy` equal to `Always` is allowed, which is the default if not specified.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.replicas` is an optional field that specifies the number of desired Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If a HorizontalPodAutoscaler (or any similar API for horizontal scaling) is managing scaling for a Deployment, don't set `.spec.replicas`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Instead, allow the Kubernetes control plane to manage the `.spec.replicas` field automatically.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.selector` is a required field that specifies a label selector for the Pods targeted by this Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.selector` must match `.spec.template.metadata.labels`, or it will be rejected by the API.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] In API version `apps/v1`, `.spec.selector` and `.metadata.labels` do not default to `.spec.template.metadata.labels` if not set.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Also note that `.spec.selector` is immutable after creation of the Deployment in `apps/v1`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment may terminate Pods whose labels match the selector if their template is different from `.spec.template` or if the total number of such Pods exceeds `.spec.replicas`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] It brings up new Pods with `.spec.template` if the number of Pods is less than the desired number.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] You should not create other Pods whose labels match this selector, either directly, by creating another Deployment, or by creating another controller such as a ReplicaSet or a ReplicationController.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If you do so, the first Deployment thinks that it created these other Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Kubernetes does not stop you from doing this.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If you have multiple controllers that have overlapping selectors, the controllers will fight with each other and won't behave correctly.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy` specifies the strategy used to replace old Pods by new ones.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.type` can be "Recreate" or "RollingUpdate".
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] All existing Pods are killed before new ones are created when `.spec.strategy.type==Recreate`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] This will only guarantee Pod termination previous to creation for upgrades.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If you upgrade a Deployment, all Pods of the old revision will be terminated immediately.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Successful removal is awaited before any Pod of the new revision is created.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If you manually delete a Pod, the lifecycle is controlled by the ReplicaSet and the replacement will be created immediately (even if the old Pod is still in a Terminating state).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The Deployment updates Pods in a rolling update fashion (gradually scale down the old ReplicaSets and scale up the new one) when `.spec.strategy.type==RollingUpdate`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] You can specify `maxUnavailable` and `maxSurge` to control the rolling update process.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxUnavailable` is an optional field that specifies the maximum number of Pods that can be unavailable during the update process.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The value can be an absolute number (for example, 5) or a percentage of desired Pods (for example, 10%).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The absolute number is calculated from percentage by rounding down.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The value cannot be 0 if `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxSurge` is 0.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For example, when this value is set to 30%, the old ReplicaSet can be scaled down to 70% of desired Pods immediately when the rolling update starts.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Once new Pods are ready, old ReplicaSet can be scaled down further, followed by scaling up the new ReplicaSet, ensuring that the total number of Pods available at all times during the update is at least 70% of the desired Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxSurge` is an optional field that specifies the maximum number of Pods that can be created over the desired number of Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The value cannot be 0 if `maxUnavailable` is 0.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The absolute number is calculated from the percentage by rounding up.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For example, when this value is set to 30%, the new ReplicaSet can be scaled up immediately when the rolling update starts, such that the total number of old and new Pods does not exceed 130% of desired Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Once old Pods have been killed, the new ReplicaSet can be scaled up further, ensuring that the total number of Pods running at any time during the update is at most 130% of desired Pods.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The Deployment controller will keep retrying the Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If specified, this field needs to be greater than `.spec.minReadySeconds`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.minReadySeconds` is an optional field that specifies the minimum number of seconds for which a newly created Pod should be ready without any of its containers crashing, for it to be considered available.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] This defaults to 0 (the Pod will be considered available as soon as it is ready).
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] To learn more about when a Pod is considered ready, see Container Probes.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Pods that become terminating due to deletion or scale down may take a long time to terminate, and may consume additional resources during that period.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] As a result, the total number of all pods can temporarily exceed `.spec.replicas`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Terminating pods can be tracked using the `.status.terminatingReplicas` field of the Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment's revision history is stored in the ReplicaSets it controls.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` is an optional field that specifies the number of old ReplicaSets to retain to allow rollback.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] These old ReplicaSets consume resources in `etcd` and crowd the output of `kubectl get rs`.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The configuration of each Deployment revision is stored in its ReplicaSets; therefore, once an old ReplicaSet is deleted, you lose the ability to rollback to that revision of Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] By default, 10 old ReplicaSets will be kept, however its ideal value depends on the frequency and stability of new Deployments.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] More specifically, setting this field to zero means that all old ReplicaSets with 0 replicas will be cleaned up.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] In this case, a new Deployment rollout cannot be undone, since its revision history is cleaned up.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.paused` is an optional boolean field for pausing and resuming a Deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The only difference between a paused Deployment and one that is not paused, is that any changes into the PodTemplateSpec of the paused Deployment will not trigger new rollouts as long as it is paused.
[src:rollback-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment is not paused by default when it is created.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:rollback-strategies/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] In database technologies, a **rollback** is an operation which returns the database to some previous state.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] Rollbacks are important for database integrity, because they mean that the database can be restored to a clean copy even after erroneous operations are performed.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] They are crucial for recovering from database server crashes; by rolling back any transaction which was active at the time of the crash, the database is restored to a consistent state.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] The rollback feature is usually implemented with a transaction log, but can also be implemented via multiversion concurrency control.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] A cascading rollback occurs in database systems when a transaction (T1) causes a failure and a rollback must be performed.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] Other transactions dependent on T1's actions must also be rollbacked due to T1's failure, thus causing a cascading effect.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] That is, one transaction's failure causes many to fail.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] Practical database recovery techniques guarantee cascadeless rollback, therefore a cascading rollback is not a desirable result.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] SQL refers to Structured Query Language, a kind of language used to access, update and manipulate database.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] In SQL, `ROLLBACK` is a command that causes all data changes since the last `START TRANSACTION` or `BEGIN` to be discarded by the relational database management systems (RDBMS), so that the state of the data is "rolled back" to the way it was before those changes were made.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] A `ROLLBACK` statement will also release any existing savepoints that may be in use.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] In most SQL dialects, `ROLLBACK`s are connection specific.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] This means that if two connections are made to the same database, a `ROLLBACK` made in one connection will not affect any other connections.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] Rollbacks are not exclusive to databases: any stateful distributed system may use rollback operations to maintain consistency.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] Examples of distributed systems that can support rollbacks include message queues and workflow management systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/rollback-data-management] More generally, any operation that resets a system to its previous state before another operation or series of operations can be viewed as a rollback.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] and transfer to the computer system(s) on which it will be run in production.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] required for the system to operate with tolerable performance and planning and/or documenting subsequent activities of the deployment process.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] for executing the software (manually or automatically).
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] and/or making all the required subsystems ready to use.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] , the main copy of the software to be used by users - "production" - might be installed on a production server in a production environment.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The **software release life cycle** is the process of developing, testing, and distributing a software product (e.g., an operating system).
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] It typically consists of several stages, such as pre-alpha, alpha, beta, and release candidate, before the final version, or "gold", is released to the public.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Pre-alpha refers to the early stages of development, when the software is still being designed and built.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha testing is the first phase of formal testing, during which the software is tested internally using white-box techniques.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Beta testing is the next phase, in which the software is tested by a larger group of users, typically outside the organization that developed it.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The beta phase is focused on reducing impacts on users and may include usability testing.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] After beta testing, the software may go through one or more release candidate phases, in which it is refined and tested further, before the final version is released.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Some software, particularly in the internet and technology industries, is released in a perpetual beta state, meaning that it is continuously being updated and improved, and is never considered to be a fully completed product.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] This approach allows for a more agile development process and enables the software to be released and used by users earlier in the development cycle.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Pre-alpha refers to all activities performed during the software project before formal testing.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] These activities can include requirements analysis, software design, software development, and unit testing.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In typical open source development, there are several types of pre-alpha versions.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] *Milestone* versions include specific sets of functions and are released as soon as the feature is complete.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The alpha phase of the release life cycle is the first phase of software testing (alpha is the first letter of the Greek alphabet, used as the number 1).
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In this phase, developers generally test the software using white-box techniques.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Additional validation is then performed using black-box or gray-box techniques, by another testing team.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Moving to black-box testing inside the organization is known as *alpha release*.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software is not thoroughly tested by the developer before it is released to customers.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software may contain serious errors, and any resulting instability could cause crashes or data loss.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software may not contain all of the features that are planned for the final version.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In general, external availability of alpha software is uncommon for proprietary software, while open source software often has publicly available alpha versions.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The alpha phase usually ends with a feature freeze, indicating that no more features will be added to the software.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] At this time, the software is said to be feature-complete.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A beta test is carried out following acceptance testing at the supplier's site (the alpha test) and immediately before the general release of the software as a product.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A **feature-complete** (FC) version of a piece of software has all of its planned or primary features implemented but is not yet final due to bugs, performance or stability issues.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] This occurs at the end of alpha testing in development.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Usually, feature-complete software still has to undergo beta testing and bug fixing, as well as performance or stability enhancement before it can go to release candidate, and finally gold status.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Beta, named after the second letter of the Greek alphabet, is the software development phase following alpha.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A beta phase generally begins when the software is feature-complete but likely to contain several known or unknown bugs.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Software in the beta phase will generally have many more bugs in it than completed software and speed or performance issues, and may still cause crashes or data loss.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The focus of beta testing is reducing impacts on users, often incorporating usability testing.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The process of delivering a beta version to the users is called *beta release* and is typically the first time that the software is available outside the organization that developed it.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Software beta releases can be either open or closed, depending on whether they are openly available or only available to a limited audience.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Beta version software is often useful for demonstrations and previews within an organization and to prospective customers.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Some developers refer to this stage as a *preview*, *preview release*, *prototype*, *technical preview* or *technology preview* (*TP*).
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Some software is kept in so-called *perpetual beta*, where new features are continually added to the software without establishing a final "stable" release.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] As the Internet has facilitated the rapid and inexpensive distribution of software, companies have begun to take a looser approach to the use of the word *beta*.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A *release candidate* (*RC*), also known as gamma testing or "going silver", is a beta version with the potential to be a stable product, which is ready to release unless significant bugs emerge.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In this stage of product stabilization, all product features have been designed, coded, and tested through one or more beta cycles with no known showstopper-class bugs.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A release is called *code complete* when the development team agrees that no entirely new source code will be added to this release.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] There could still be source code changes to fix defects, changes to documentation and data files, and peripheral code for test cases or utilities.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Also called *production release*, the *stable release* is the last *release candidate* (*RC*) which has passed all stages of verification and tests.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Any known remaining bugs are considered acceptable.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Linux distributions like Debian) also have *long-term support* (*LTS*) releases which are based on full releases that have already been tried and tested and receive only security updates.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Once released, the software is generally known as a "stable release".
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The formal term often depends on the method of release: physical media, online release, or a web application.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Usually the released software is assigned an official version name or version number.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] (Pre-release software may or may not have a separate internal project code name or internal version number).
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The term "release to manufacturing" (RTM), also known as "going gold", is a term used when a software product is ready to be delivered.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] This build may be digitally signed, allowing the end user to verify the integrity and authenticity of the software purchase.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The RTM build is known as the "gold master" or GM is sent for mass duplication or disc replication if applicable.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The terminology is taken from the audio record-making industry, specifically the process of mastering.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] RTM precedes general availability (GA) when the product is released to the public.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A golden master build (GM) is typically the final build of a piece of software in the beta stages for developers.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Typically, for iOS, it is the final build before a major release, however, there have been a few exceptions.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] RTM could also mean in other contexts that the software has been delivered or released to a client or customer for installation or distribution to the related hardware end user computers or machines.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The term does *not* define the delivery mechanism or volume; it only states that the quality is sufficient for mass distribution.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The deliverable from the engineering organization is frequently in the form of a golden master media used for duplication or to produce the image for the web.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] During its supported lifetime, the software is sometimes subjected to service releases, patches or service packs, sometimes also called "interim releases" or "maintenance releases" (MR).
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] For example, Microsoft released three major service packs for the 32-bit editions of Windows XP and two service packs for the 64-bit editions.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Such service releases contain a collection of updates, fixes, and enhancements, delivered in the form of a single installable package.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Some software is released with the expectation of regular support.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Classes of software that generally involve protracted support as the norm include anti-virus suites and massively multiplayer online games.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Continuing with this Windows XP example, Microsoft did offer paid updates for five more years after the end of extended support.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] This means that support ended on April 8, 2019.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] After the end-of-life date, the developer will usually not implement any new features, fix existing defects, bugs, or vulnerabilities (whether known before that date or not), or provide any support for the product.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] If the developer wishes, they may release the source code, so that the platform may be maintained by volunteers.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Usage of the "alpha/beta" test terminology originated at IBM.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Similar terminologies for IBM's software development were used by people involved with IBM from at least the 1950s (and probably earlier).
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] "A" test was the verification of a new product before the public announcement.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The "B" test was the verification before releasing the product to be manufactured.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The "C" test was the final test before the general availability of the product.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] As software became a significant part of IBM's offerings, the alpha test terminology was used to denote the pre-announcement test and the beta test was used to show product readiness for general availability.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Martin Belsky, a manager on some of IBM's earlier software projects claimed to have invented the terminology.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] IBM dropped the alpha/beta terminology during the 1960s, but by then it had received fairly wide notice.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The usage of "beta test" to refer to testing done by customers was not done in IBM.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Major public betas developed afterward, with early customers having purchased a "pioneer edition" of the WordVision word processor for the IBM PC for $49.95.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In 1984, Stephen Manes wrote that "in a brilliant marketing coup, Bruce and James Program Publishers managed to get people to *pay* for the privilege of testing the product." In September 2000, a *boxed version* of Apple's Mac OS X Public Beta operating system was released.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Between September 2005 and May 2006, Microsoft released *community technology preview*s (*CTP*s) for Windows Vista.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] From 2009 to 2011, *Minecraft* was in public beta.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In February 2005, ZDNet published an article about the phenomenon of a beta version often staying for years and being used as if it were at the production level.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] It noted that Gmail and Google News, for example, had been in beta for a long time although widely used; Google News left beta in January 2006, followed by Google Apps (now named Google Workspace), including Gmail, in July 2009.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Since the introduction of Windows 8, Microsoft has called pre-release software a *preview* rather than *beta*.
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] All pre-release builds released through the Windows Insider Program launched in 2014 are termed "Insider Preview builds".
[src:rollback-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] "Beta" may also indicate something more like a release candidate, or as a form of time-limited demo, or marketing technique.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:rollback-strategies/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
